data.content:
This code **does not use `Thread.Abort`** — so there's nothing to migrate on that front. It uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep`, all of which still work in .NET 8.

That said, the raw `Thread` pattern is outdated. The modern .NET 8 equivalent uses `Task` / `Parallel`:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        await Parallel.ForEachAsync(items, async (item, ct) =>
        {
            await Task.Run(() => Process(item), ct);
        });
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

**Key `Thread.Abort` migration notes** (for when you encounter it elsewhere):

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 Replacement |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `CancellationToken` + cooperative cancellation |
| `ThreadAbortException` | `OperationCanceledException` |
| `Thread.Sleep(ms)` | `await Task.Delay(ms, ct)` |

`Thread.Abort()` **throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET 8. Replace it with:

```csharp
// Pass CancellationToken into your work methods
private void Process(WorkItem item, CancellationToken ct)
{
    ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative check
    item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
}

// Cancel via CancellationTokenSource instead of Thread.Abort
var cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
cts.Cancel(); // instead of thread.Abort()
```

**Bottom line:** Your posted code is already safe for .NET 8 — no `Thread.Abort` present. Just modernize to `Task`/`Parallel` for better resource usage.
